I think there are two different intuitive models of payment for order flow.=
 Let=E2=80=99s call them the Good Model and the Bad Model.=C2=A0The Good Mo=
del goes like this. Lots of retail investors go to their brokerage looking =
to buy XYZ stock, and lots of retail investors go to their brokerage lookin=
g to sell XYZ stock. XYZ is available on the stock exchange; you can buy it=
 for $10.02 or sell it for $9.98. Those prices on the stock exchange are ca=
lled the =E2=80=9Cnational best bid and offer,=E2=80=9D or NBBO, and are se=
t essentially by market makers, high-frequency electronic traders who are i=
n the business of buying from sellers and selling to buyers. The spread =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the $0.04 difference between the buying price (the offer) and t=
he selling price (the bid)[1] =E2=80=94=C2=A0is due to the fact that the ma=
rket makers take lots of risk: If they buy stock on the stock exchange, pro=
bably some smart hedge fund is selling, and it will probably go down. So th=
ey need to buy at a fairly low price ($9.98) and sell at a fairly high pric=
e ($10.02) to compensate for this risk of =E2=80=9Cadverse selection,=E2=80=
=9D this risk that whoever they trade with knows something that they don=E2=
=80=99t.If the brokerage just sends all of its customers=E2=80=99 orders to=
 the stock exchange, they will buy at $10.02 and sell at $9.98, which is no=
t so great. Also the brokerage will pay a little fee =E2=80=94=C2=A0customa=
rily $0.003 per share =E2=80=94=C2=A0to the exchange for executing the orde=
r.But the market makers come to the brokerage=C2=A0and say: Look, we=C2=A0h=
ate=C2=A0trading with all these hedge funds on the public stock exchange. S=
o much adverse selection. If we could just trade with your delightful retai=
l customers, who trade small lots and=C2=A0never know anything we don=E2=80=
=99t know, we would never lose money. So we could afford to charge them a m=
uch lower spread. So if you send your orders to us directly, we will let yo=
ur customers buy at $10.01 and sell at $9.99. They will get a better price =
than they would on the stock exchange, but we will still make money. Not on=
ly that! We=E2=80=99ll make so much money that we can pay you some of it. W=
e=E2=80=99ll give you $0.003 per share for your trouble. Instead of you pay=
ing an exchange to execute your customers=E2=80=99=C2=A0orders, we=E2=80=99=
ll pay you to execute them. With that money, you can fund your business. It=
 can replace commissions! You can offer free trades! Good deal for everyone=
.The Good Model has very intuitive market-structure economics. I have=C2=A0=
discussed it in more detail a few times, mainly here.=C2=A0The Bad Model go=
es like this. XYZ is available on the stock exchange, and the posted prices=
 are in fact $10.02 to buy and $9.98 to sell. But only naive rubes pay thos=
e posted prices. There is a =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D price to buy XYZ, a savv=
y-customer price that you can get by knowing where XYZ is on sale. The real=
 price is, say, $10.001 to buy and $9.999 to sell.[2] You have to be smart,=
 you have to know about order types and hidden liquidity and dark pools, yo=
u can=E2=80=99t just send a market order to the big stock exchange and expe=
ct to get the real price. But lots of people are smart; there are smart ord=
er routers that are commercially available and that are good at finding the=
 real price.High-frequency electronic traders, for instance, are smart, and=
 know where to find the real price. They can easily buy XYZ for $10.001 and=
 sell it for $9.999. Retail customers of retail brokerages are not particul=
arly smart, and frankly the retail=C2=A0brokerages=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t all =
that smart; they don=E2=80=99t know where to find the real price. All they =
know is that the posted price, the NBBO, is $9.98 / $10.02.So the electroni=
c traders =E2=80=94=C2=A0the market makers =E2=80=94=C2=A0go to the brokera=
ges and say: Look. Instead of sending your customers=E2=80=99 orders to the=
 exchange, having them pay $10.02 and get $9.98 and you paying $0.003 in fe=
es, send their orders to us. We=E2=80=99ll give them a better price; we=E2=
=80=99ll charge them $10.01 to buy and pay them $9.99 to sell. And we=E2=80=
=99ll even pay you $0.003 for your trouble. This is a good deal for the bro=
kerage (it gets paid for order flow instead of paying for execution), and i=
t=C2=A0looks like=C2=A0a good deal for the customers (they pay $10.01 inste=
ad of $10.02, etc.).But meanwhile the market makers are doing this very sim=
ple trade:=09Customer comes to them to buy stock.=09It sells them stock for=
 $10.01.=09It turns around and buys stock at the real price, $10.001.=09It =
makes $0.009 in instant risk-free profit.=09It pays $0.003 of that to the b=
rokerage for the opportunity.The Bad Model is what pretty much everyone bel=
ieves about payment for order flow. It is the explicit model of Michael Lew=
is=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CFlash Boys.=E2=80=9D I have discussed it in more deta=
il here, when we talked about an institutional brokerage that followed it m=
ore or less exactly and got in trouble with the Securities and Exchange Com=
mission. The brokerage told its customers that it did smart routing to try =
to find them the best price. But it didn=E2=80=99t: It secretly sold their =
orders to market makers who filled the orders at a better-than-the-NBBO-but=
-worse-than-the-best-price price, and then went out and traded for themselv=
es at the best price.[3]By the way, I call it the Bad Model, because people=
 seem to think that it=E2=80=99s bad.=C2=A0Maybe that is unfair. Maybe I sh=
ould call the Good Model the =E2=80=9CPrincipal Model,=E2=80=9D and the Bad=
 Model the =E2=80=9CAgency Model.=E2=80=9D In the Principal (Good) Model, t=
he market makers are essentially in the business of=C2=A0intermediating tra=
des between retail customers in time:=C2=A0The economic theory of the marke=
t maker=E2=80=99s job is that it buys from retail sellers, waits, sells to =
retail buyers, and collects a small spread representing its relatively low =
risk of adverse selection.In the Agency (Bad) Model, the market makers are =
essentially in the business of=C2=A0finding good liquidity and selling it t=
o retail:=C2=A0The economic theory of the market maker=E2=80=99s job is tha=
t it buys from retail sellers and immediately resells at a higher price bec=
ause it knows where the higher prices are, but since the retail customer do=
esn=E2=80=99t know where the higher prices are the market maker is providin=
g a useful service.I think that in the real world both of these models have=
 to be somewhat true. That is, in the real world, what happens is that a ma=
rket maker buys stock from a retail brokerage=E2=80=99s customers thousands=
 of times each day, and sometimes it then turns around and sells the stock =
to that brokerage=E2=80=99s customers a minute later and collects a small s=
pread (Good Model), and other times it turns around and sells the stock at =
the midpoint on a dark pool a millisecond later (Bad Model), and other time=
s it does other things (sells the stock at the NBBO for risk management and=
 loses money? I dunno) not really captured by either model. The market make=
rs who internalize retail brokerage flow do not=C2=A0only=C2=A0do that; the=
y also trade on public exchanges and dark pools and with institutional inve=
stors, and they manage their risk holistically and you cannot separate out =
which model they follow.Still, the two models do make different empirical p=
redictions. In particular they make different predictions about=C2=A0what w=
ould happen if a retail brokerage =E2=80=94=C2=A0or every retail brokerage =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0stopped using payment for order flow and routing orders to m=
arket makers:=09On the Good Model, internalizing retail orders allows them =
to get better prices than they could get in public markets, so getting rid =
of this model would lead to worse prices for retail.=09On the Bad Model, in=
ternalizing retail orders allows them to get=C2=A0worse=C2=A0prices than th=
ey could get in the (=E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D) public markets, so getting rid=
 of this model would lead to better prices for retail,=C2=A0if=C2=A0retail =
brokers can do a good job of finding the real best public price.Last week P=
ublic, a retail stock brokerage, put out a Medium post titled =E2=80=9CDeli=
vering on Price Execution Without PFOF.=E2=80=9D (Felix Salmon wrote about =
it here.) Earlier this year Public said that it would stop taking payment f=
or order flow; instead, it routes its orders to public venues. Here=E2=80=
=99s how that=E2=80=99s going:The takeaway: The data available to us strong=
ly suggests that Public delivers better execution quality on average to cus=
tomers than our peer firms that accept PFOF from market makers. =E2=80=A6We=
 want our customers to get the best possible price on every single order. S=
o, working with our partners at Apex Clearing, Instinet and the execution v=
enues, we use smart order routing (=E2=80=9CSOR=E2=80=9D) software to locat=
e the best price for each order available across 28 different lit exchanges=
 and alternative trading systems (=E2=80=9CATSs=E2=80=9D), and then route t=
hat order to the venue that offers the best price.When a customer submits a=
n order to Public, the SOR first tries to execute that order at the =E2=80=
=9Cmidpoint=E2=80=9D price that is halfway between the Best Bid and Best Of=
fer by scanning venues that are often not included in NBBO, including retai=
l-specific lit venues and alternative trading systems that are designed to =
pair natural buyers and sellers at the midpoint.If we are unable to find a =
NBBO midpoint (or similar) execution during this first sweep, we route to t=
he exchange with the best available posted price (often called the =E2=80=
=9Cinside quote=E2=80=9D) as well as the highest likelihood of executing th=
e order at or better than the NBBO. Most often, these are high-quality lit =
exchanges, including Nasdaq and IEX.This approach is working. We=E2=80=99re=
 able to deliver better prices for our investors, in aggregate, than the PF=
OF-based model. This is based largely on delivering significantly better pr=
ices for a meaningful percentage of our investors=E2=80=99 orders.There are=
 some statistics comparing execution quality and suggesting that Public get=
s better prices without the payment-for-order-flow model than it would with=
 that model. Which suggests that the Bad Model of PFOF might predominate.So=
me caveats:=09There are different ways to measure execution quality across =
lots of trades, none of the data is that transparent, and no study is ever =
really definitive. Some orders presumably get better execution with a PFOF/=
internalizer model, but others get better execution without it; Public=E2=
=80=99s aggregate numbers are good =E2=80=9Cbased largely on delivering sig=
nificantly better prices for a meaningful percentage of our investors=E2=80=
=99 orders.=E2=80=9D I think that means something like =E2=80=9Cwe trade at=
 the midpoint=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0$10.00 in my schematic examples above=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ca lot of the time, which is way more price improve=
ment than internalizers offer, but when we don=E2=80=99t get a midpoint fil=
l=C2=A0we are more likely to end up trading at the NBBO, which is less pric=
e improvement than internalizers would offer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=09This is not =
complete support for the Bad Model, because part of how Public gets good pr=
ices is by sending orders to =E2=80=9Cretail-specific lit venues,=E2=80=9D =
that is, places for people who want to trade with retail due to, basically,=
 the economic theory of the Good Model. =E2=80=9CIt is desirable to trade a=
gainst retail,=E2=80=9D the basic theory of the Good Model, does seem to be=
 true.=09Public=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t get paid for order flow, and in fact o=
ften pays exchanges to execute orders, which means that its business is not=
 subsidized by PFOF, which makes it harder to offer free trading. (Public o=
ffers free trading, but gently requests tips.) If you think free trading is=
 good then this is a drawback to getting rid of PFOF. (If you think free tr=
ading is bad and encourages gambling and churn, then this is a benefit!)Sti=
ll all in all this does count as evidence for the Bad Model: You can find s=
tock for sale at better prices than the NBBO, if you look for it, so you do=
n=E2=80=99t have to use payment for order flow to get good execution for re=
tail orders.
