      Retail options
   =20
 =20
Last week Vice published an article=C2=A0with the headline =E2=80=9CI Lost =
$400,000, Almost Everything I Had, on a Single Robinhood Bet.=E2=80=9D The =
bet was a $200-strike call option on Alibaba Group Holding Ltd. in February=
, when Alibaba was trading in the mid-$200s. Basically buying an in-the-mon=
ey call option like that is a way to get a lot of leverage on a stock: You =
pay, say, $60 for an option on a share worth $240; you get four-to-one leve=
rage, which is more than=C2=A0you can get in a U.S. margin account. Then if=
 the stock goes up to $300, you get back $100, for a $40 profit on a $60 in=
vestment. If the stock goes down to $200=C2=A0you get back nothing, for a $=
60 loss. =E2=80=9CMy thesis was I might not make a lot of money, but I won=
=E2=80=99t lose much,=E2=80=9D says the article.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe downside=
 seemed limited.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0What?=C2=A0This person put $400,000 into thi=
s trade and lost all of it.Is this bad? I don=E2=80=99t know. It seems bad.=
 How do you prevent it? At some level you might want each retail investor t=
o have some trusted fiduciary financial adviser and have to run all of thei=
r trades through that adviser. You call up the adviser and say =E2=80=9Chey=
 I=E2=80=99d like to put all my money into Alibaba call options=E2=80=9D an=
d the adviser says =E2=80=9Care you sure=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Cyes=
=E2=80=9D and she says =E2=80=9Cthis is unbelievably dumb=E2=80=9D and you =
say =E2=80=9Cnonetheless=E2=80=9D and she says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll let yo=
u put 10% of your money into Alibaba call options, max,=E2=80=9D and you sa=
y =E2=80=9Cno I want all of it=E2=80=9D and she says =E2=80=9Cnope=E2=80=9D=
 and her ruling is final. Obviously the market cannot actually work like th=
is. You have to be able to do the dumb things that you want to do. Sometime=
s you shouldn=E2=80=99t, though.Today the Wall Street Journal has an articl=
e titled =E2=80=9CInvestors Are Using Robinhood, Other Platforms to Jump In=
to Options Trades, Worrying U.S. Regulators.=E2=80=9D What can the regulato=
rs do about it? Well, one thing they can do is complain that you used to ha=
ve to call someone to do an options trade:=E2=80=9CNow, the ability to trad=
e options is just a few clicks away, and investors can easily trade without=
 direct contact with their brokers,=E2=80=9D Securities and Exchange Commis=
sioner Caroline Crenshaw said in a recent speech. =E2=80=9CGiven these chan=
ges in market access, it may be that the options account approval rules are=
 due for a review.=E2=80=9DShe said that when the current options-approval =
rules were written=E2=80=94in 1980=E2=80=94investors had direct contact wit=
h a human broker who could explain the impact of various strategies and the=
 risks they entailed.Which is a reasonable complaint! =E2=80=9CA human brok=
er=E2=80=9D is not the same as =E2=80=9Ca trusted fiduciary financial advis=
er,=E2=80=9D and if you called up a broker in the =E2=80=9980s and said =E2=
=80=9Cput all my money in one call option=E2=80=9D she might have said =E2=
=80=9Csure chief=E2=80=9D and taken the commission. There is some chance sh=
e would not have. That is sort of a crazy thing to do and she might have ta=
lked you out of it. She wants the commission, but if you lose all your mone=
y in a week then she=E2=80=99s not getting any=C2=A0more=C2=A0commissions o=
ut of you. Long-term greedy, etc.=C2=A0Still, complaining that things were =
better in the olden days is not really something=C2=A0useful=C2=A0that regu=
lators can do about this. Instead they might tinker with options approval=
=C2=A0rules:Gaining approval to buy and sell options through some brokerage=
s, such as Robinhood Markets Inc., is significantly easier than at others. =
Such discrepancies, combined with the recent trading surge, has left U.S. r=
egulators questioning whether the rules governing individual investors=E2=
=80=99 access to the options market need to be revised.Because of the risks=
, brokers have long been required to perform extra due diligence before app=
roving someone to trade options. This includes obtaining information about =
the customer=E2=80=99s financial background and investment experience, and =
making sure the customer has been apprised of the risks.Representatives fro=
m the Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association, a lobbying gro=
up for brokers and asset managers, have met with officials at Finra and the=
 SEC in recent months to discuss potential changes. The group recommended s=
tandardizing the different levels that brokers use when approving customers=
 to trade options. =E2=80=A6Still, other brokers are much more rigorous in =
reviewing customers=E2=80=99 applications to trade options. Some large brok=
erages require investors to speak to a representative and answer questions =
about options trading before approving them to do more-complex trades. It c=
an take days to review applications for the most basic level of options tra=
ding at some.Robinhood, by contrast, approves investors=E2=80=99 applicatio=
ns instantly if their responses to the questionnaire meet the company=E2=80=
=99s criteria.This does not strike me as all that useful either? The person=
 in the Vice article did a very simple options strategy =E2=80=94=C2=A0just=
 buying a call option, not a =E2=80=9Cmore-complex trade=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and my impression is that he or she understood perfectly how the trad=
e worked. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8BI would describe a call option as a le=
veraged bet on an underlying stock, which helps you increase the upside (or=
 downside) of the bet you're trying to make,=E2=80=9D the person wrote, acc=
urately capturing how the trade operated and also how it blew up. The probl=
em is not understanding; the problem is deciding to put 100% of your assets=
 into one leveraged stock bet.=C2=A0It is not impossible to regulate agains=
t that! Make a rule that no one can buy options with more than 10% of their=
 net worth or whatever. It just seems very hard politically. U.S. financial=
 regulation just isn=E2=80=99t structured like that; rather than paternalis=
tic limits on investment we have disclosure requirements. Disclosure does n=
ot seem sufficient to prevent people from losing all of their money on one =
call options trade.=C2=A0People like a gamble, and the system is set up to =
give them one.
