<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PFOF</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think there are two different intuit=
ive models of payment for order flow. Let=E2=80=99s call them the Good Mode=
l and the Bad Model.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Good Model g=
oes like this. Lots of retail investors go to their brokerage looking to bu=
y XYZ stock, and lots of retail investors go to their brokerage looking to =
sell XYZ stock. XYZ is available on the stock exchange; you can buy it for =
$10.02 or sell it for $9.98. Those prices on the stock exchange are called =
the =E2=80=9Cnational best bid and offer,=E2=80=9D or NBBO, and are set ess=
entially by market makers, high-frequency electronic traders who are in the=
 business of buying from sellers and selling to buyers. The spread =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the $0.04 difference between the buying price (the offer) and the =
selling price (the bid)[1] =E2=80=94=C2=A0is due to the fact that the marke=
t makers take lots of risk: If they buy stock on the stock exchange, probab=
ly some smart hedge fund is selling, and it will probably go down. So they =
need to buy at a fairly low price ($9.98) and sell at a fairly high price (=
$10.02) to compensate for this risk of =E2=80=9Cadverse selection,=E2=80=9D=
 this risk that whoever they trade with knows something that they don=E2=80=
=99t.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the brokerage just sends all of it=
s customers=E2=80=99 orders to the stock exchange, they will buy at $10.02 =
and sell at $9.98, which is not so great. Also the brokerage will pay a lit=
tle fee =E2=80=94=C2=A0customarily <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/25970842.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9zcG90bGlnaHQvZW=
1zYWMvbWVtby1tYWtlci10YWtlci1mZWVzLW9uLWVxdWl0aWVzLWV4Y2hhbmdlcy5wZGY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBcf931d56" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">$0.003 per share</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
o the exchange for executing the order.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=
 the market makers come to the brokerage=C2=A0and say: Look, we=C2=A0<em>ha=
te=C2=A0</em>trading with all these hedge funds on the public stock exchang=
e. So much adverse selection. If we could just trade with your delightful r=
etail customers, who trade small lots and=C2=A0<em>never</em> know anything=
 we don=E2=80=99t know, we would never lose money. So we could afford to ch=
arge them a much lower spread. So if you send your orders to us directly, w=
e will let your customers buy at $10.01 and sell at $9.99. They will get a =
better price than they would on the stock exchange, but we will still make =
money. Not only that! We=E2=80=99ll make so much money that we can pay you =
some of it. We=E2=80=99ll give you $0.003 per share for your trouble. Inste=
ad of you paying an exchange to execute your customers=E2=80=99=C2=A0orders=
, we=E2=80=99ll pay you to execute them. With that money, you can fund your=
 business. It can replace commissions! You can offer free trades! Good deal=
 for everyone.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Good Model has very intu=
itive market-structure economics. I have=C2=A0discussed it in more detail a=
 few times, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/259708=
42.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtM=
DItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVy=
LWZsb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIwODIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjA4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB045dfbf1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">mainly here</a>.=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Bad Model goes like this. XYZ is available on the=
 stock exchange, and the posted prices are in fact $10.02 to buy and $9.98 =
to sell. But only naive rubes pay those posted prices. There is a =E2=80=9C=
real=E2=80=9D price to buy XYZ, a savvy-customer price that you can get by =
knowing where XYZ is on sale. The real price is, say, $10.001 to buy and $9=
.999 to sell.[2] You have to be smart, you have to know about order types a=
nd hidden liquidity and dark pools, you can=E2=80=99t just send a market or=
der to the big stock exchange and expect to get the real price. But lots of=
 people are smart; there are smart order routers that are commercially avai=
lable and that are good at finding the real price.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">High-frequency electronic traders, for instance, are smart, and kno=
w where to find the real price. They can easily buy XYZ for $10.001 and sel=
l it for $9.999. Retail customers of retail brokerages are not particularly=
 smart, and frankly the retail=C2=A0<em>brokerages=C2=A0</em>aren=E2=80=99t=
 all that smart; they don=E2=80=99t know where to find the real price. All =
they know is that the posted price, the NBBO, is $9.98 / $10.02.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the electronic traders =E2=80=94=C2=A0the market m=
akers =E2=80=94=C2=A0go to the brokerages and say: Look. Instead of sending=
 your customers=E2=80=99 orders to the exchange, having them pay $10.02 and=
 get $9.98 and you paying $0.003 in fees, send their orders to us. We=E2=80=
=99ll give them a better price; we=E2=80=99ll charge them $10.01 to buy and=
 pay them $9.99 to sell. And we=E2=80=99ll even pay you $0.003 for your tro=
uble. This is a good deal for the brokerage (it gets paid for order flow in=
stead of paying for execution), and it=C2=A0<em>looks like=C2=A0</em>a good=
 deal for the customers (they pay $10.01 instead of $10.02, etc.).</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But meanwhile the market makers are doing this very=
 simple trade:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px=
; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Customer comes to t=
hem to buy stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It sells them st=
ock for $10.01.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It turns around an=
d buys stock at the real price, $10.001.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">It makes $0.009 in instant risk-free profit.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">It pays $0.003 of that to the brokerage for the opportuni=
ty.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Bad Model is what pretty much=
 everyone believes about payment for order flow. It is the explicit model o=
f Michael Lewis=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CFlash Boys.=E2=80=9D I have discussed it=
 in more detail <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25=
970842.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jEtMDktMjMvZGFyay1wb29sLXNvbGQtc29tZS1vcmRlci1mbG93P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEyMDgyMV9N=
T05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJ=
tPTIxMTIwOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1bd1e1=
f1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">here</a>, when we talked about an <em>institutional</em> broke=
rage that followed it more or less exactly and got in trouble with the Secu=
rities and Exchange Commission. The brokerage told its customers that it di=
d smart routing to try to find them the best price. But it didn=E2=80=99t: =
It secretly sold their orders to market makers who filled the orders at a b=
etter-than-the-NBBO-but-worse-than-the-best-price price, and then went out =
and traded for themselves at the best price.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">By the way, I call it the Bad Model, because people seem to think that=
 it=E2=80=99s bad.=C2=A0Maybe that is unfair. Maybe I should call the Good =
Model the =E2=80=9CPrincipal Model,=E2=80=9D and the Bad Model the =E2=80=
=9CAgency Model.=E2=80=9D In the Principal (Good) Model, the market makers =
are essentially in the business of=C2=A0<em>intermediating trades between r=
etail customers in time:=C2=A0</em>The economic theory of the market maker=
=E2=80=99s job is that it buys from retail sellers, waits, sells to retail =
buyers, and collects a small spread representing its relatively low risk of=
 adverse selection.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the Agency (Bad) Mod=
el, the market makers are essentially in the business of=C2=A0<em>finding g=
ood liquidity and selling it to retail:=C2=A0</em>The economic theory of th=
e market maker=E2=80=99s job is that it buys from retail sellers and immedi=
ately resells at a higher price because it knows where the higher prices ar=
e, but since the retail customer doesn=E2=80=99t know where the higher pric=
es are the market maker is providing a useful service.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">I think that in the real world both of these models have to be =
somewhat true. That is, in the real world, what happens is that a market ma=
ker buys stock from a retail brokerage=E2=80=99s customers thousands of tim=
es each day, and sometimes it then turns around and sells the stock to that=
 brokerage=E2=80=99s customers a minute later and collects a small spread (=
Good Model), and other times it turns around and sells the stock at the mid=
point on a dark pool a millisecond later (Bad Model), and other times it do=
es other things (sells the stock at the NBBO for risk management and loses =
money? I dunno) not really captured by either model. The market makers who =
internalize retail brokerage flow do not=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>do that; t=
hey also trade on public exchanges and dark pools and with institutional in=
vestors, and they manage their risk holistically and you cannot separate ou=
t which model they follow.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, the two m=
odels do make different empirical predictions. In particular they make diff=
erent predictions about=C2=A0what would happen if a retail brokerage =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0or every retail brokerage =E2=80=94=C2=A0stopped using payment for=
 order flow and routing orders to market makers:</p><ol style=3D"list-style=
-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">On the Good Model, internalizing retail orders allows them t=
o get better prices than they could get in public markets, so getting rid o=
f this model would lead to worse prices for retail.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">On the Bad Model, internalizing retail orders allows them=
 to get=C2=A0<em>worse=C2=A0</em>prices than they could get in the (=E2=80=
=9Creal=E2=80=9D) public markets, so getting rid of this model would lead t=
o better prices for retail,=C2=A0<em>if=C2=A0</em>retail brokers can do a g=
ood job of finding the real best public price.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Last week Public, a retail stock brokerage, <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25970842.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly9tZWRpdW0uY29=
tL3RoZS1wdWJsaWMtYmxvZy9kZWxpdmVyaW5nLW9uLXByaWNlLWV4ZWN1dGlvbi13aXRob3V0LX=
Bmb2YtMjdmMGU2MDk4YTJm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB63eb5f97" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">put out a=
 Medium post</a> titled =E2=80=9CDelivering on Price Execution Without PFOF=
.=E2=80=9D (Felix Salmon<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/25970842.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYXhpb3MuY29tL2EtbmV3LWNhc2UtYWdhaW5zd=
C1wYXltZW50LWZvci1vcmRlci1mbG93LWQzNTZlNTY5LTcxNjMtNDlkZi04MTM1LTc0YTNhODUx=
ZjZmMS5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB10a49562" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote about it her=
e</a>.) Earlier this year <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/25970842.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly9tZWRpdW0uY29tL3RoZS1wdWJsaWMtYmxvZy9hbGl=
nbmluZy13aXRoLW91ci1jb21tdW5pdHktMzAwODg1Nzk5ZDAz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
145b4ebf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">Public said</a> that it would stop taking payment for ord=
er flow; instead, it routes its orders to public venues. Here=E2=80=99s how=
 that=E2=80=99s going:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The take=
away: The data available to us strongly suggests that Public delivers bette=
r execution quality on average to customers than our peer firms that accept=
 PFOF from market makers. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We want=
 our customers to get the best possible price on every single order. So, wo=
rking with our partners at Apex Clearing, Instinet and the execution venues=
, we use smart order routing (=E2=80=9CSOR=E2=80=9D) software to locate the=
 best price for each order available across 28 different lit exchanges and =
alternative trading systems (=E2=80=9CATSs=E2=80=9D), and then route that o=
rder to the venue that offers the best price.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">When a customer submits an order to Public, the SOR first tries to execu=
te that order at the =E2=80=9Cmidpoint=E2=80=9D price that is halfway betwe=
en the Best Bid and Best Offer by scanning venues that are often not includ=
ed in NBBO, including retail-specific lit venues and alternative trading sy=
stems that are designed to pair natural buyers and sellers at the midpoint.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If we are unable to find a NBBO midpoint (=
or similar) execution during this first sweep, we route to the exchange wit=
h the best available posted price (often called the =E2=80=9Cinside quote=
=E2=80=9D) as well as the highest likelihood of executing the order at or b=
etter than the NBBO. Most often, these are high-quality lit exchanges, incl=
uding Nasdaq and IEX.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This approach is work=
ing. We=E2=80=99re able to deliver better prices for our investors, in aggr=
egate, than the PFOF-based model. This is based largely on delivering signi=
ficantly better prices for a meaningful percentage of our investors=E2=80=
=99 orders.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are some sta=
tistics comparing execution quality and suggesting that Public gets better =
prices without the payment-for-order-flow model than it would with that mod=
el. Which suggests that the Bad Model of PFOF might predominate.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some caveats:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decima=
l; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">There are different ways to measure execution quality across lots of trad=
es, none of the data is that transparent, and no study is ever really defin=
itive. Some orders presumably get better execution with a PFOF/internalizer=
 model, but others get better execution without it; Public=E2=80=99s aggreg=
ate numbers are good =E2=80=9Cbased largely on delivering significantly bet=
ter prices for a meaningful percentage of our investors=E2=80=99 orders.=E2=
=80=9D I think that means something like =E2=80=9Cwe trade at the midpoint=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0$10.00 in my schematic examples above =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9Ca lot of the time, which is way more price improvement than int=
ernalizers offer, but when we don=E2=80=99t get a midpoint fill=C2=A0we are=
 more likely to end up trading at the NBBO, which is less price improvement=
 than internalizers would offer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">This is not complete support for the Bad Model, because part =
of how Public gets good prices is by sending orders to =E2=80=9Cretail-spec=
ific lit venues,=E2=80=9D that is, places for people who want to trade with=
 retail due to, basically, the economic theory of the Good Model. =E2=80=9C=
It is desirable to trade against retail,=E2=80=9D the basic theory of the G=
ood Model, does seem to be true.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">P=
ublic=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t get paid for order flow</em>, and in fact of=
ten pays exchanges to execute orders, which means that its business is not =
subsidized by PFOF, which makes it harder to offer free trading. (Public of=
fers free trading, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/25970842.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly9oZWxwLnB1YmxpYy5jb20vZW4vYXJ0aWNsZXMvNDg0OT=
E4MS11cGRhdGluZy1ob3ctd2UtbWFrZS1tb25leS1hbmQtaW50cm9kdWNpbmctdGlwcGluZw/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0525503e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">gently requests tips</a>.) If you =
think free trading is good then this is a drawback to getting rid of PFOF. =
(If you think free trading is bad and encourages gambling and churn, then t=
his is a benefit!)</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still all in all t=
his does count as evidence for the Bad Model: You can find stock for sale a=
t better prices than the NBBO, if you look for it, so you don=E2=80=99t hav=
e to use payment for order flow to get good execution for retail orders.</p=
><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" width=3D"auto" cellpadding=
=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"2" align=3D"left" valign=3D"top" style=3D"padding:0 0px">=20
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25970842.263649/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9zbGkuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9jbGljaz9zPTgyNTkyOSZsaT0yNTk3MDg0MiZtPTIxZ=
