-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Retail options</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25970842.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudmljZS5jb20vZW=
4vYXJ0aWNsZS9idm5uM2EvaS1sb3N0LWRvbGxhcjQwMDAwMC1hbG1vc3QtZXZlcnl0aGluZy1pL=
WhhZC1vbi1hLXNpbmdsZS1yb2Jpbmhvb2QtYmV0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6217c314" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">Vice published an article</a>=C2=A0with the headline =E2=80=9CI Los=
t $400,000, Almost Everything I Had, on a Single Robinhood Bet.=E2=80=9D Th=
e bet was a $200-strike call option on Alibaba Group Holding Ltd. in Februa=
ry, when Alibaba was trading in the mid-$200s. Basically buying an in-the-m=
oney call option like that is a way to get a lot of leverage on a stock: Yo=
u pay, say, $60 for an option on a share worth $240; you get four-to-one le=
verage, which is more than=C2=A0you can get in a U.S. margin account. Then =
if the stock goes up to $300, you get back $100, for a $40 profit on a $60 =
investment. If the stock goes down to $200=C2=A0you get back nothing, for a=
 $60 loss. =E2=80=9CMy thesis was I might not make a lot of money, but I wo=
n=E2=80=99t lose much,=E2=80=9D says the article.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe downsid=
e seemed limited.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>What?=C2=A0</em>This person put $400,00=
0 into this trade and lost all of it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is th=
is bad? I don=E2=80=99t know. It seems bad. How do you prevent it? At some =
level you might want each retail investor to have some trusted fiduciary fi=
nancial adviser and have to run all of their trades through that adviser. Y=
ou call up the adviser and say =E2=80=9Chey I=E2=80=99d like to put all my =
money into Alibaba call options=E2=80=9D and the adviser says =E2=80=9Care =
you sure=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D and she says =E2=80=9Ct=
his is unbelievably dumb=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Cnonetheless=E2=80=9D=
 and she says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll let you put 10% of your money into Alib=
aba call options, max,=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=9Cno I want all of it=E2=
=80=9D and she says =E2=80=9Cnope=E2=80=9D and her ruling is final. Obvious=
ly the market cannot actually work like this. You have to be able to do the=
 dumb things that you want to do. Sometimes you shouldn=E2=80=99t, though.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Today the Wall Street Journal has an articl=
e titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
25970842.263649/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9pbnZlc3RvcnMtYXJlLXV=
zaW5nLXJvYmluaG9vZC1vdGhlci1wbGF0Zm9ybXMtdG8tanVtcC1pbnRvLW9wdGlvbnMtdHJhZG=
VzLXdvcnJ5aW5nLXUtcy1yZWd1bGF0b3JzLTExNjM4ODg2MTA5P21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3Bvczc/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0792482c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Investors Are Using Robinhood, Ot=
her Platforms to Jump Into Options Trades, Worrying U.S. Regulators</a>.=E2=
=80=9D What can the regulators do about it? Well, one thing they can do is =
complain that you used to have to call someone to do an options trade:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CNow, the ability to trade =
options is just a few clicks away, and investors can easily trade without d=
irect contact with their brokers,=E2=80=9D Securities and Exchange Commissi=
oner Caroline Crenshaw said in a recent speech. =E2=80=9CGiven these change=
s in market access, it may be that the options account approval rules are d=
ue for a review.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">She said that whe=
n the current options-approval rules were written=E2=80=94in 1980=E2=80=94i=
nvestors had direct contact with a human broker who could explain the impac=
t of various strategies and the risks they entailed.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which is a reasonable complaint! =E2=80=9CA human br=
oker=E2=80=9D is not the same as =E2=80=9Ca trusted fiduciary financial adv=
iser,=E2=80=9D and if you called up a broker in the =E2=80=9980s and said =
=E2=80=9Cput all my money in one call option=E2=80=9D she might have said =
=E2=80=9Csure chief=E2=80=9D and taken the commission. There is some chance=
 she would not have. That is sort of a crazy thing to do and she might have=
 talked you out of it. She wants the commission, but if you lose all your m=
oney in a week then she=E2=80=99s not getting any=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>c=
ommissions out of you. Long-term greedy, etc.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Still, complaining that things were better in the olden days is no=
t really something=C2=A0<em>useful=C2=A0</em>that regulators can do about t=
his. Instead they might tinker with options approval=C2=A0rules:</p><blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gaining approval to buy and sell options =
through some brokerages, such as Robinhood Markets Inc., is significantly e=
asier than at others. Such discrepancies, combined with the recent trading =
surge, has left U.S. regulators questioning whether the rules governing ind=
ividual investors=E2=80=99 access to the options market need to be revised.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because of the risks, brokers have long be=
en required to perform extra due diligence before approving someone to trad=
e options. This includes obtaining information about the customer=E2=80=99s=
 financial background and investment experience, and making sure the custom=
er has been apprised of the risks.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Represen=
tatives from the Securities Industry and Financial Markets Association, a l=
obbying group for brokers and asset managers, have met with officials at Fi=
nra and the SEC in recent months to discuss potential changes. The group re=
commended standardizing the different levels that brokers use when approvin=
g customers to trade options. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sti=
ll, other brokers are much more rigorous in reviewing customers=E2=80=99 ap=
plications to trade options. Some large brokerages require investors to spe=
ak to a representative and answer questions about options trading before ap=
proving them to do more-complex trades. It can take days to review applicat=
ions for the most basic level of options trading at some.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Robinhood, by contrast, approves investors=E2=80=99 applicat=
ions instantly if their responses to the questionnaire meet the company=E2=
=80=99s criteria.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This does no=
t strike me as all that useful either? The person in the Vice article did a=
 very simple options strategy =E2=80=94=C2=A0just buying a call option, not=
 a =E2=80=9Cmore-complex trade=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and my impression is=
 that he or she understood perfectly how the trade worked. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=
=8B=E2=80=8BI would describe a call option as a leveraged bet on an underly=
ing stock, which helps you increase the upside (or downside) of the bet you=
're trying to make,=E2=80=9D the person wrote, accurately capturing how the=
 trade operated and also how it blew up. The problem is not understanding; =
the problem is deciding to put 100% of your assets into one leveraged stock=
 bet.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not impossible to regulat=
e against that! Make a rule that no one can buy options with more than 10% =
of their net worth or whatever. It just seems very hard politically. U.S. f=
inancial regulation just isn=E2=80=99t structured like that; rather than pa=
ternalistic limits on investment we have disclosure requirements. Disclosur=
e does not seem sufficient to prevent people from losing all of their money=
 on one call options trade.=C2=A0People like a gamble, and the system is se=
t up to give them one.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" =
cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
